dium, and during the last decade it has become increasingly clear how much these investigations have to offer to contemporary debates about ecology, the age of the anthropocene and the potentialities of new digital technologies. In James Benning’s Environments a range of international scholars highlight the thematic and formal coherence of Benning’s practice, whilst providing readers with an artistic and historical context to understand his experimental film work. The volume offers a number of interpretative frameworks drawing on film theory, environmental humanities, visual culture and philosophy, explaining why Benning has emerged as one of today’s essential filmmakers.Key FeaturesContextualises Benning’s work in relation to the most important artistic and socio-historical influences on his filmmakingAnalyses Benning as an eco-filmmaker with perspectives from environmental studies and eco-cinemaOffers philosophical approaches to Benning’s films in view of their aesthetic, political and epistemological import  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEcocriticism. 0aEcology in motion pictures. 0aEnvironmentalism in motion pictures. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / Direction & Production.2bisacsh1 aBeck, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiagioli, Kriss, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColman, Felicity, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConley, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardner, Colin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLübecker, Nikolaj, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacDonald, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPanse, 